===Ben Lomond===
The Ben Lomond nation consisted of at least three clans totalling 150–200 people. They occupied the 260 km2 of country surrounding the [[Ben Lomond (Tasmania)|Ben Lomond]] plateau. Three clan names are known but their locations are somewhat conjectural - the clans were recorded as Plangermaireener, Plindermairhemener and Tonenerweenerlarmenne.{{sfn|Ryan|2012|p=32}}{{sfn|Plomley|2008|p=1005}}

The Plangermaireener clan is recorded as variously inhabiting the south-east aspect of the Ben Lomond region and also has been associated with the Oyster Bay or Cape Portland Clans to the east - indeed the chief [[Mannalargenna]] is variously described as a chief of the Oyster Bay, Cape Portland and Ben Lomond nations.{{sfn|Mannalargenna}}{{sfn|Ryan|2012|p=20}}
Plangermaireener is also used as a blanket term for the Ben Lomond nation, which reflects the suffix "mairreener"; meaning "people".{{sfn|Plomley|1992b|p=13}}

The Plindermairhemener are recorded in association with the south and south-western aspects of the region{{sfn|Plomley|2008|p=1005}}{{sfn|Plomley|1992b|p=20}}{{sfn|Kee|1991|p=?}}{{sfn|Hansen|2004|p=125}} and the location of the Tonenerweenerlarmenne is uncertain, but were probably centred in the remaining Ben Lomond nation territory from White Hills to the headwaters of the North and South-Esk rivers or the upper South-Esk Valley.{{sfn|Syme|Ball|Elder|2012}}
This notwithstanding, the Palawa were a nomadic people and likely occupied these lands seasonally.{{sfn|Ryan|2012|p=32}}

The Ben Lomond nation is sometimes described as the Ben Lomond/Pennyroyal Creek nation from an entry in [[George Augustus Robinson|Robinson]]'s journal:
'(Mannalargenna) ... said that "the smoke...was that of the Ben Lomond-Pennyroyal Creek natives"'{{sfn|Plomley|2008|p=315}}

This is a misnomer, as the Pennyroyal Creek was the original European name for the [[Liffey River (Tasmania)|Liffey River]] and the Pennyroyal Creek Tribe was the contemporary name of the Panninher Clan of the North Midlands nation.{{sfn|Plomley|1992b|p=31}}{{sfn|Plomley|2008|p=1011}}
Mannalargenna would be familiar with the clans neighbouring his own traditional country and could be relied upon to report accurately the composition of the clanspeople in question. It is plausible that when Robinson was writing in 1830 the remnant peoples of the Ben Lomond nation had federated with that of the Panninher and this was the provenance of the conjoined title.

====Seasonal movement====
The clans of the Ben Lomond nation were nomadic and the Aborigines hunted along the valleys of the [[South Esk River|South Esk]] and [[North Esk River|North Esk]] rivers, their tributaries and the highlands to the northeast; as well as making forays to the plateau in summer. There are records of aboriginal huts or dwellings around the foothills of [[Stacks Bluff]] and around the headwaters of the South Esk River near modern-day Mathinna.{{sfn|Kee|1991|p=?}} On the plateau there is evidence of artifacts around Lake Youl that suggests regular occupation of this site by aborigines after the last ice age.{{sfn|Kee|1991|p=?}} The clans of the Ben Lomond nation had close enough relationships with neighbouring clans of the East Coast and North Midlands that they enjoyed seasonal foraging rights to these adjoining territories.{{sfn|Ryan|2012|p=32}} [[John Batman]] describes the seasonal movement of the Plangermaireener in his diary of May 1830:

''"...the tribe travels around Ben Lomond from South Esk to North Esk - and from thence to St. Patricks Head - Georges Bay and round the East Coast"''{{sfn|Kee|1991|p=?}}

Batman further describes the relationship between the clans of the Ben Lomond nation and the North East nation:

''"...there is (sic) two tribes... they (the 'chiefs' ) are upon friendly terms and often stop and meet and talk 10 days together..."''{{sfn|Kee|1991|p=?}}
