{{Infobox Newspaper |name = P.M. News |logo = PM News logo.gif |type = Daily newspaper |format = |foundation = 1994 |ceased publication = |price = |owners = |publisher = Independent Communications Network Limited |editor = [[Lanre Babalola]] |language = English |circulation = 60,000 copies daily |headquarters = [[Lagos]] |website = http://pmnewsnigeria.com }} '''''P.M. News''''' is a daily newspaper published in [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]] by the Independent Communications Network Limited (ICNL). The company also publishes the weekly ''TheNEWS'' magazine and ''Tempo'', a tabloid.<ref name=AboutUs/>
'''''The News''''' was founded in 1993 by Bayo Onanuga, [[Babafemi Ojudu]] and other former staff from the African Concord who had resigned in protest over a request by [[M.K.O. Abiola]], the publisher, to apologise to President [[Ibrahim Babangida]] over a critical story about the military regime. Ojudu was the first Managing Editor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://babafemiojudu.org/about-babafemi.html |title=About Babafemi |publisher=Babafemi Ojudu |accessdate=2011-05-10}}</ref> After harassment by the Babangida regime, there was a brief period of press freedom under General [[Sani Abacha]] during which ''P.M. News'' was launched in August 1994 as a breezy afternoon paper strongly oriented towards news but also covering fashions, sports and entertainment.<ref name=AboutUs/>
In the years that followed, ''P.M. News'' and ''TheNews'' were known for "guerrilla journalism".<ref name=cjfe1998/> They were subject to constant interference by the authorities, arrests and closures.<ref name=AboutUs/> For example, in August 1996 [[Amnesty International]] reported that Editor-in-chief Bayo Onanuga was thought to be held by the [[State Security Service (Nigeria)|State Security Service]] at their Lagos headquarters, and may have been ill-treated in custody. Babafemi Ojudu had been released on 13 August 1996 and had required hospital treatment as a result of ill-treatment. The two men may have been arrested due to publishing articles critical to the government.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/AFR44/021/1996/en |publisher=Amnesty International |accessdate=2011-05-12 |title=Nigeria: Fear of ill-treatment / possible prisoner of conscience: Bayo Onanuga |date=14 August 1996}}</ref> Onanuga fled from Nigeria in 1997 after hiding from state security forces for months. He returned home to resume work at ICNL in 1998, after the sudden death of Abacha and the start of the transition to democracy.<ref name=cjfe1998/>
==References== {{reflist |refs= <ref name=AboutUs>{{cite web |url=http://pmnewsnigeria.com/about-2/ |title=About Us |publisher=Independent Communications Network Limited |accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> <ref name=cjfe1998>{{cite web |url=http://www.cjfe.org/cjfe_gala/award_winners/Bayo_Onanuga |publisher=Canadian Journalists for Free Expression |title=Bayo Onanuga, Nigeria |date=1998 |accessdate=2011-05-12}}</ref> }} {{Major Nigerian newspapers}}
