{{refimprove|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox album | name = Sol Filosofia | type = [[Album]] | artist = [[Sauti Sol]] | cover = Sauti Sol - Sol Filosofia.jpg | alt = | released = 25 February 2011 | recorded = | venue = | studio = | genre = [[Afro pop music|Afro-pop]] | length = 40:20 | label = Penya Records | producer = Wawesh | prev_title = [[Mwanzo]] | prev_year = 2009 | next_title = [[Live and Die in Afrika]] | next_year = 2015 }} '''''Sol Filosofia''''' is the second [[studio album]] by Kenyan [[afro pop music|afro-pop]] band [[Sauti Sol]]. It was released on February 25, 2011 by Penya Records, and launched at the [[Alliance française]] in [[Nairobi]].<ref name="one">{{cite web|url=http://nairobinow.wordpress.com/2011/02/04/concertalbum-launch-sol-filosofia-feb-25-2011-alliance-francaise-garden/ |title=Concert/Album Launch: Sol Filosofia, Feb. 25 2011 @ Alliance Française Garden |date=4 February 2011 |work=Nairobi Now |accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref>
The album's two singles "Soma Kijana" and "Coming Home" also had music videos released, with that of the latter featuring
==Singles== * "Soma Kijana" was released as the album's [[lead single]]. It urges all youth to take education seriously and read. The song's genre was inspired by one of Sauti Sol's biggest inspirations, the late [[Daudi Kabaka]].{{Citation needed|reason=This claim needs a reliable source. |date=August 2014}} * "Coming Home" was released as the album's second single. A music video for the song was released on 13 April 2011, and featured singer and reality star Patricia Kihoro. In the video, guitarist Polycarp Otieno finds himself rejected by his girlfriend soon after the band returns home from tour, pushing him to take his own life as his fellow band members try to save him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dhq46syzJI4 |title=Sauti Sol "Coming Home" |date=13 April 2011 |publisher=Marko Roca on [[YouTube]] |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> A sequel of the song is said to be in production. The song won the Best Music Video award at the 2011 [[Kisima Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kisimaawards.co.ke/kisima42011/ |title=The 2011 Kisima Music Awards Winners |publisher=[[Kisima Music Awards]] |accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref>
==Track listing== Track listing for ''Sol Filosofia'' adapted from [[Amazon.com]].<ref name="two">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Sauti-Sol-Filosofia/dp/B0050S7PNC |title=Sol Filosofia – Sauti Sol |date=25 February 2011 |publisher=[[Amazon.com]] |accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref> {{Tracklisting | title1 = Mbinguni | length1 = 5:01 | title2 = Malikia | length2 = 3:59 | title3 = Coming Home | length3 = 4:43 | title4 = Soma Kijana | length4 = 4:03 | title5 = Awinja | length5 = 5:30 | title6 = Bowana Lelisu | length6 = 2:37 | title7 = Nambee | length7 = 5:37 | title8 = L.A.D.Y. | length8 = 5:17 | title9 = Row Your Boat | length9 = 4:20 | title10 = Sofia | length10 = 4:40 | title11 = Private Spice | length11 = 3:56 | title12 = Sol Generation | length12 = 3:46 }}
